		<div id="comment_body_64569235"><blockquote><div><p>Radar didn't exist before WW2 and with that came all kinds of benefits for navigation and weather forecasting, which is just one example.</p></div></blockquote><p>That isn't even true.  The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_Home" title="wikipedia.org">Chain Home</a> [wikipedia.org] early warning radar was rolled out starting in 1937 and was in full-time operation in 1938.  The first operational <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freya_radar" title="wikipedia.org">Freya</a> [wikipedia.org] units were also delivered in 1938.  Radar was an obvious idea by the 1930s, and WW2 just happened to coincide with the period when it became practical.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64569235">

</div>
